S. Korean cameramen issue statement 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) -- 139 South Korean cameramen reportedly called a press conference in front of the U.S. embassy on Dec. 12 at which they released a "statement of 100 cameramen demanding a proper settlement of the case of girl students."
 The U.S. Forces' probe into the grievous death of the two girl students and their trial of the killers were so shocking that one could not but deplore the incompetence and status of South Koreans, the statement said, and continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The recent trial is invalid. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The death of the girl students should be reinvestigated from the beginning and those responsible for it should be called to account. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The only way of preventing the recurrence of such tragedy is to immediately revise the unequal South Korea-U.S. Status of Forces Agreement. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the end of the press conference, the cameramen staged a silent demonstration and moved to the venue of a citizens rally to encourage Buddhists in their sit-in hunger strike.

Preventing conservative forces from coming to power called for in S. Korea
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) -- The south headquarters of the National Alliance of Youth and Students for the Country's Reunification reportedly released an "article to all the people, youth and students" in South Korea on Dec. 12, calling for preventing the conservative forces from coming to power.
 The article said that the "presidential election" would be the "watershed of life or death" deciding whether to liquidate the old politics or not and whether to implement the June 15 joint declaration or not. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the conservative forces are allowed to come to power, they will bring the second economic crisis and the second June 25 Korean War and the movement for independence, democracy and reunification and potential progressive politics will be stifled and the June 15 joint declaration be reduced to a dead document, the article said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The article called on all youth and students to take part in the "election" under this rigorous situation to open new politics and a new phase of implementing the joint declaration and counter the U.S. interference in "election" with high vigilance.

Early reconnection of inter-Korean rail and road links called for
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) -- The mine-clearing in the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) along the military demarcation line was completed as of Dec. 14 for the projects of reconnecting rail and road links between the north and the south of Korea. This has made it possible to push ahead with the projects in real earnest.
 This is a shining fruition of the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration, a landmark of national reunification, and a product of the desire of all the Koreans and efforts exerted by them to rejoin the ties of the nation and reunify the divided land. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The projects of reconnecting the east and west coastal rail and road links open a bright prospect of boosting the inter-Korean cooperation, exchange, reconciliation and unity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 When the projects are completed, inter-Korean visits will become more frequent and the South Korean tourists who had to come to Mt. Kumgang only by ships will be able to travel overland. As a result, the number of tourists will sharply increase. This will also open a bright prospect of investing in the Kaesong Industrial Zone where the ground is expected to be broken soon. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The inter-Korean railway project is of great international significance as it will be linked to the trans-Siberian railroad in Russia in the future. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The project of connecting Korea-Russia railways will be greatly conducive to boosting economic ties and cooperation not only between the DPRK and Russia but among countries in Northeast Asia and Europe and, furthermore, achieving peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific region and the rest of the world and the common prosperity of humankind. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 That is why the whole world is supporting and welcoming these gigantic railway projects. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 But it is only the united states which is getting in the way of the projects. The U.S. has pursued only inter-Korean confrontation, not peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
It attempted to derail the reconnection of north-south rail and road links, talking about a "list of verification group" and "permit." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This put the once brisk mine-clearing project in the DMZ in stalemate for some time when it was at its final phase. But it was resumed and finally completed thanks to the inter-Korean cooperation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The north-south rail and road links will be reconnected without fail thanks to the concerted efforts of all the Koreans.

U. S. denounced for its hostile policy toward DPRK
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) -- Guy Dupre, secretary general of the International Liaison Committee for Reunification and Peace in Korea, released a statement on Dec. 11 denouncing the U.S. for its hostile policy toward the DPRK.
 He in the statement said that the white paper released by the DPRK National Reunification Institute on Dec. 6 cited the irrefutable evidence to show that the U.S. has historically blocked the process of reconciliation, cooperation, peace and reunification on the Korean Peninsula whenever progress has been made in the process. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He said: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Soon after its emergence, the Bush administration declared invalid all the agreements reached between the preceding administration and North Korea, and has been escalating its moves to isolate and stifle North Korea as never before. It is also rendering the situation on the Korean Peninsula strained to attain its aims. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He called on all the peace-loving and progressive forces of the world to oppose the u.s. hostile policy toward the DPRK and further strengthen the solidarity movement for reunification and peace in Korea.

Remarks of commander of U.S. marines in Japan blasted
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) - The commander of the U.S. marines in Japan, addressing a press conference, on Dec. 13 let loose extremely provocative war outcries, faulting the independent step taken by the DPRK against the U.S. actual stop of the supply of heavy oil, an abandonment of its commitment under the Geneva Agreed Framework, according to JIJI Press. 
 He hinted that a U.S. carrier may be dispatched to waters off the Korean Peninsula in case the situation gets worse, blustering that it is closely watching the moves of the DPRK in the wake of its decision to restart its nuclear facilities. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 These remarks made by the commander of the U.S. marines in Japan which have played the role of vanguard and shock force in the U.S. overseas war of aggression are little short of hinting the second Korean War as they were timed to coincide with the evermore pronounced hostile policy of the Bush administration toward the DPRK, its increasing threat of "preemptive nuclear attack" and its piracy committed against a trading ship of the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What arouses the DPRK's vigilance is the fact that these outcries came at a time when warhawks of the United States and South Korea held an "annual security consultative meeting" in Washington on Dec. 6 at which they decided to make joint military counteraction against the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 "Military counteraction" precisely means a declaration of a war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. intention to dispatch a carrier to waters off the Korean Peninsula means that the "military counteraction" is becoming a reality. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 While paying lip-service to the peaceful solution to the nuclear issue on the Korean Peninsula, the U.S. is taking dangerous military moves, increasing its pressure upon the DPRK to scrap its "nuclear development program through possible verification" after turning aside from the DPRK's proposal for concluding a non-aggression treaty with the U.S. in actuality. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This goes to clearly prove that the United States has become more undisguised in its moves to disarm the DPRK by force and destroy its system. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 There is no need to explain what the appearance of a U.S. carrier in waters off the Korean Peninsula means at a time when there is a serious crisis due to the nuclear issue brought up by the United States. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The revolutionary armed forces for self-defence of the DPRK are closely watching the evermore undisguised military moves of the U.S. bellicose forces. They will not allow the enemies to invade territorial waters, air and land of the DPRK but deal telling blows at them.

U.S. urged to stop anti-DPRK burlesque
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) -- Part 20 of the American film "James Bond-007" and other films to be shown in South Korea at the end of this month is a product of the U.S. administration's policy of despising the Korean nation and its hostile policy toward the DPRK. That is why this is intolerable.
 Rodong Sinmun today says this in a signed commentary demanding the U.S. stop the anti-DPRK burlesque against the Korean nation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 From the outset of their production, the films caused trouble because they are based on the theme intended to insult the Korean nation, the commentary notes, and goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. is locked in the noisy "nuclear racket" against the DPRK and depriving the people in South Korea of their sovereignty, dignity and right to existence. As if it were not enough with this, the U.S. is misusing even a movie, a product of human civilization, for the purpose of its policy of despising the Korean nation. It is not hard to guess what is the U.S. real intention. The U.S. seeks to bar the Koreans in the north and the south from getting united and perpetuate the division of Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
To this end the U.S. produced and is showing such anti-reunification film against the Korean nation despite protest from all the Koreans. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Korean nation is a dignified nation who values self-respect more than its life and soul. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. is well advised to stop at once the anti-DPRK burlesque against the Koreans, clearly understanding the will of the Korean nation not to allow any act of infringing upon their dignity but to force the U.S. to pay a high price for it.

Japan warned not to follow U.S. policy
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) -- Japan stands at the crossroads: whether it will precipitate its isolation and downfall, following the anachronistic U.S. policy toward the DPRK or it will take the road of co-existence and co-prosperity in the spirit of the DPRK-Japan Pyongyang declaration, says Rodong Sinmun today in a signed commentary.
 A news analyst says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Japanese imperialists committed thrice-cursed crimes against the Korean people in the past. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The liquidation of the past is at the core of the declaration and it is the master key to the improved bilateral relations. 
 Putting aside the liquidation of the past, however, ultra right-wing conservatives of Japan are projecting the issue of some abducted Japanese and hatching fresh plots for an anti-DPRK campaign. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The reactionaries of Japan, dancing to the tune of the U.S. in its efforts to isolate and stifle the DPRK, described joint military manoeuvres with the U.S. as "ones to deter attack from North Korea" under the pretext of its nuclear issue. They have gone the length of saying that "Japan may fight a war with North Korea." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan's joining the U.S. in the strategy to invade Korea and Asia is little short of digging its own grave by itself. 
 If Japan dares violate the spirit of the declaration, dancing to the tune of the U.S., it will be held wholly responsible for the ensuing consequences.

U.S. President's phone "apology" under fire
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, December 17 (KCNA) -- The headquarters of the People's Movement for the Withdrawal of the U.S. Troops From South Korea and the "presidential election" struggle headquarters of the Seoul District Federation of University Student Councils reportedly denounced the U.S. President for his deceptive "apology" over the phone.
 The headquarters of the people's movement for the withdrawal of the U.S. troops from South Korea issued a commentary headlined "Bush's apology is no more than playing with semantics" on Dec. 14. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The commentary said that Bush's "apology" should have referred to the issue of the withdrawal of the U.S. troops. His attitude trying to gloss over the murder case, by way of excuse, not mentioning such core articles, is not a sincere apology. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the U.S. is to make a real apology for the case of killing Hyo Sun and Mi Son, it should send the GI murderers again to the court of South Korea, immediately revise the Status of Forces Agreement and put forward the timetable for the withdrawal of the U.S. troops before the people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The struggle headquarters of students in a commentary on Dec. 13 said that Bush's "apology" is essentially intended to calm down the ever-mounting anti-U.S. sentiments and control a spate of demonstrations.

Second inter-Korean Red Cross working contact held
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kumgangsan, December 17 (KCNA) -- The second north-south Red Cross working contact was held at Mt. Kumgang Resort from Dec. 15 to 17.
 According to a joint release published at the contact, both sides expressed the same view on the issue of a site for a meeting house at Mt. Kumgang, the issue of its designing and the issue of forming a "working group for its construction" and agreed in principle upon and the issue of arranging the 6th reunion of separated families and relatives on the occasion of the lunar New Year in Juche 92 (2003). &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They agreed to continue the discussion on the scale of the house, the whereabouts of separated families and relatives and their correspondence, the whereabouts of those missing during the Korean War, etc. at the next contact. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They also agreed to continue the discussion at the third north-south Red Cross contact in January Juche 92 (2003) on the basis of the issues discussed at this contact.

Inter-Korean working-level contact held 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kumgangsan, December 17 (KCNA) -- The 3rd working-level contact of the panel for the reconnection of rail and road links between the north and the south was held from Dec. 15 to 17 at Mt. Kumgang Resort.
 According to a joint release published at the contact, the north and the south agreed to make positive efforts to ensure that the projects of reconnecting inter-Korean rail and roads links are completed in accordance with the agreed schedule and cooperate with each other in the efforts to make sure the equipment and materials needed for the projects are supplied according to its schedule. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Both sides agreed to open to traffic a temporary road for the transport of equipment and materials needed for the projects and personnel and equipment necessary for the construction of Kaesong Industrial Zone before the ground is broken for its construction. In this regard they agreed to recommend to their military authorities to have discussions on the opening of the temporary road on the west coast and the passage through temporary roads on the east and west coasts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They agreed to effectuate at an early date a basic agreement on the transit vehicles on the road through he exchange of necessary signed documents and adopt a basic agreement on the operation of trains as soon as possible through the exchange of documents. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They agreed to hold the second meeting of the panel for the reconnection of rail and road links between the north and the south in Pyongyang in mid-January, Juche 92 (2003).
